description:
Large inference models (LRMs) significantly improve performance by generating long-chain inference, but this also introduces serious problems of redundant inference, computational overhead, and inference runaway. Existing methods (such as Self-Braking Tuning) typically rely on the detection and post-processing of redundant steps, essentially remaining "external constraints." This paper proposes a novel training and tuning paradigm&mdash;Flow-Constrained Reasoning (FCR)&mdash;which fundamentally models the inference process as a dynamic system satisfying network flow conservation constraints.  
 &nbsp; 
  In this framework, inference steps are treated as nodes in a graph, and information transfer is modeled as a directed flow with capacity and cost. By introducing flow conservation constraints, capacity limits, and potential function learning based on dual variables, the model can automatically adjust the length and structure of inference paths during generation. Furthermore, we propose a minimum-cut-based inference termination mechanism, enabling the model to intrinsically learn when to stop inference, thereby avoiding overthinking.  
 &nbsp; 
  The core breakthrough of this method lies in transforming the "inference length control problem" into a "flow optimization problem" and enabling the model to learn the implicit optimal flow structure through end-to-end training, thereby achieving a balance between inference efficiency and performance.

